  <data name="Page.Personal.Title" xml:space="preserve"><value>Personal vaults</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Personal.Desc" xml:space="preserve"><value>Your private vaults for personal logins, secure notes and other secrets. They belong to you alone — encrypted so that nobody else, not even an administrator, can read them. Use them the way you would a personal password manager: store a login per website, reveal the password only when you need it, and organize items into folders.</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Team.Title" xml:space="preserve"><value>Team vaults</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Team.Desc" xml:space="preserve"><value>Vaults owned by your organization (tenant) and shared with colleagues through access grants. Use them for credentials a team needs in common — shared service accounts, Wi-Fi keys, licence keys — where you decide per person who may read, edit or manage each vault. Sharing is explicit: a colleague sees only the vaults you grant them.</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Secrets.Title" xml:space="preserve"><value>Software credentials</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Secrets.Desc" xml:space="preserve"><value>Software credentials are the machine secrets your applications need at runtime — API keys, connection strings, signing keys and the like — stored encrypted and grouped by environment (Development / Test / Preview / Production). Instead of putting these values in your app's own config files, your deployed software fetches them from here at startup through the read API, using a client token. On this page you create and manage the values; on the Client tokens page you issue the tokens your software uses to read them.</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Tokens.Title" xml:space="preserve"><value>Client tokens</value></data>
  <data name="Page.Tokens.Desc" xml:space="preserve"><value>Client tokens let your deployed software authenticate to AM KEYWARD and read this project's software credentials at runtime — so secrets never have to live in the app's own config. Each token is scoped to a single environment, so a leaked Production token still cannot read Development. The token's secret value is shown only once, when you issue it — copy it immediately and store it in your app's configuration.</value></data>
