  <data name="Token.UsageNote" xml:space="preserve"><value>How to use it: store the token in your deployed app's configuration (an environment variable or secret store), then have the app call AM KEYWARD's read API with the header “Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;” to load this project's secrets for its environment, typically at startup. Secrets therefore never live in your app's own files. If a token leaks, Rotate it to replace its value or Revoke it to disable it — your other tokens keep working.</value></data>
  <data name="Secret.UsageNote" xml:space="preserve"><value>How it fits together: you store a value here once per environment; your deployed software reads it at runtime with a client token (see the Client tokens page). Change a value here and the next read picks it up — no redeploy of your app needed.</value></data>
